<br>
+ If a rogue has time to prepare, he'll open with a poison.  These are somewhat harder to resist than comperable spells usually, and save agains poison.  Odds are he'll use a snare.  Other options are blind, weaken, mana drain, or DoT.  Mostly it'll be a snare, though.  These can't be removed by cancel magic - they need cure poison.<br>
<br>
+ A smart rogue, if given the chance, will use pumice to get rid of any of the oponent's buffs, or sometimes his own debuffs.  Pumice has a long casting time and rogues have 0 channellign skill.  I suppose it would be quite an irony for a wizard to interrupt a rogue's casting with a stab.  (Okay, that's not reallistic, I know.)  He will definitely pumice off your damage shield, if he can.  Odds are, he'll try to get rid of your see invis, too, if it's not item based.<br>
<br>
+ Fade spells are very disorienting.  It takes time to locate the wizard again.  I wonder if it would make sense for the wizard to use short-range fades and quick-casting blasts, instead of the big heavy ones?<br>
<br>
+ A bow can be used to help locate a target.  Messages like, &quot;You cannot hit your target from here&quot;, &quot;Your target is out of range&quot;, and &quot;Your target is too far above/below you&quot; can give excellent hints on where to look for someone who got away.<br>
<br>
+ If there's a lull in the fight, odds are the rogue is either binding wounds or applying more poison.<br>
<br>
+ Due to lag issues, it is *much* harder for a melee to hit a target that's moving.  If the rogue is stuck to you and you're waiting for those spell gems to ungrey, run.<br>
<br>
I certainly don't claim to know it all.  This is just my perspective from occasional PvP events on a blue server. <p><B>Bayler Briggan Soulblade</B><BR>
